The Herald Ishemunyoro Chingwere in Hwange
President Mnangagwa has deplored Zimbabwe’s legacy failures which have resulted in the importation of power despite its huge generation capacity. <img class="wp-image-496905 size-full" src="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ED-3.jpg" alt="" width="700" height="467" srcset="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ED-3.jpg 700w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ED-3-360x240.jpg 360w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ED-3-680x454.jpg 680w" sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" /> President Mnangagwa tour Dinson Colliery mine in Hwange The President expressed these sentiment when he toured Zambezi Gas and Coal Mine here. He is on a two-day working visit of coal projects in Hwange. <img class="aligncenter wp-image-496908 size-full" src="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ED-2.jpg" alt="" width="700" height="467" srcset="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ED-2.jpg 700w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ED-2-360x240.jpg 360w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ED-2-680x454.jpg 680w" sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" />Speaking after touring Zambezi Gas and Coal Mine, President Mnangagwa said Zimbabwe should not be spending hundreds of millions in US Dollars importing power. Zimbabwe augments it’s power needs with imports from South Africa and Mozambique. <img class="aligncenter wp-image-496910 size-full" src="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ED-1.jpg" alt="" width="700" height="506" srcset="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ED-1.jpg 700w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ED-1-360x260.jpg 360w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ED-1-680x492.jpg 680w" sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" />“You (Finance and Economic Development Minister Mthuli Ncube) are spending hundreds of millions a month importing power when we have everything to produce power in this country,” said the President. <img class="aligncenter wp-image-496917 size-large" src="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ed3-680x453.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="453" srcset="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ed3-680x453.jpg 680w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ed3-360x240.jpg 360w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ed3-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ed3.jpg 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> “Yesterday, where we visited and the general picture I have been given now, is that we should be energy sufficient by 2023,” he said. <img class="aligncenter wp-image-496911 size-large" src="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ed2-680x453.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="453" srcset="https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ed2-680x453.jpg 680w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ed2-360x240.jpg 360w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ed2-768x512.jpg 768w, https://www.herald.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/2/2020/07/ed2.jpg 1080w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> The President said he was disappointed to learn that at some stage Zimbabwe imported coal due to mining inefficiencies.